726
00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.050
Rule number three, don't take notes.

727
00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:51.960
There's no need to sit down and
note down in a notebook what you learned

728
00:43:52.030 --> 00:43:56.930
in the course because it's not effective.

729
00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.650
There's an alternative cost to everything.

730
00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:03.290
If If you take notes,
those minutes you waste taking notes,

731
00:44:03.360 --> 00:44:06.890
you could have spent those minutes doing
another repetition, listen another time,

732
00:44:06.960 --> 00:44:09.530
and that is so much more effective.

733
00:44:09.600 --> 00:44:12.050
It's not that notes are bad.

734
00:44:12.120 --> 00:44:13.450
Notes are not bad.

735
00:44:13.520 --> 00:44:19.250
But I wouldn't spend my time
taking any notes.

736
00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:21.090
Notes is a thing of the past.

737
00:44:21.160 --> 00:44:23.970
We used to take notes
in school or at university.

738
00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:27.130
We used to do homework
in school and universities.

739
00:44:27.200 --> 00:44:29.720
Forget about that.
This is a completely new method.

740
00:44:29.790 --> 00:44:32.090
It doesn't require
any notes, any homework.

741
00:44:32.160 --> 00:44:37.250
It just requires you being focused
and following the steps one by one.

742
00:44:37.320 --> 00:44:39.450
That's rule number 3.

743
00:44:39.520 --> 00:44:43.090
Rule number 4, don't ask why.

744
00:44:43.160 --> 00:44:44.370
Don't ask why.

745
00:44:44.440 --> 00:44:51.250
This is apretty correlated
to rule number three.

746
00:44:51.320 --> 00:44:52.930
Don't ask why.

747
00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:59.050
This means don't ask, "why
is the sentence structured this way?"

748
00:44:59.120 --> 00:45:01.730
"Why do they say this and not this?"

749
00:45:01.800 --> 00:45:05.410
"Why is it pronounced this
way and not this way?"

750
00:45:05.480 --> 00:45:07.210
"Why, why, why?"

751
00:45:07.280 --> 00:45:08.810
Don't ask why.

752
00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:13.450
Because when you ask the question "why",
you're looking for a logical answer.

753
00:45:13.520 --> 00:45:17.050
You're looking
for a theoretical answer, right?

754
00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:21.130
We don't learn languages
through theory or through explanations

755
00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:23.330
or through decoding the language.

756
00:45:23.400 --> 00:45:27.080
We learn languages by
adopting the child mentality.

757
00:45:27.150 --> 00:45:30.530
A child, when he or she learns
his first language,

758
00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:32.690
they don't question the language.

759
00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:35.210
They just consume,
and they let the language

760
00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:37.450
come to them effortlessly over time.

761
00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:40.210
If they don't understand anything,
they don't question it.

762
00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:44.210
They just continue consuming,
and they will learn it eventually.

763
00:45:44.280 --> 00:45:48.810
If they make a bunch of mistakes in their
pronunciation, they don't care about it.

764
00:45:48.880 --> 00:45:50.760
They don't ask,
"Why am I saying this wrong?"

765
00:45:50.830 --> 00:45:53.250
"How can I pronounce this better?"

766
00:45:53.320 --> 00:45:56.890
No, they just continue with
the method over and over again.

767
00:45:56.960 --> 00:46:00.930
And over time, they correct their own
mistakes, and they improve.

768
00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.690
So don't ask why.

769
00:46:03.760 --> 00:46:08.800
I know this completely different to
how you're used to learning a language.

770
00:46:08.870 --> 00:46:12.960
I know you're used to having
a teacher maybe giving you tips

771
00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:14.850
on your pronunciation when you speak.

772
00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:16.450
It's not effective.

773
00:46:16.520 --> 00:46:19.410
It's not going to make you learn faster.

774
00:46:19.480 --> 00:46:21.730
Trust me, don't ask why.

775
00:46:21.800 --> 00:46:27.120
Just continue studying, consuming,
and over time, you will correct yourself

776
00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:32.890
and you will fix the small errors,
and you will understand everything.

777
00:46:32.960 --> 00:46:35.522
But naturally, intuitively.

778
00:46:35.722 --> 00:46:40.360
You won't know why you
structure a sentence one way

779
00:46:40.430 --> 00:46:44.170
or another, just as you don't
know that stuff in Spanish either.

780
00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:46.650
In your native language,
you don't know the rules, but you

781
00:46:46.720 --> 00:46:48.890
speak it perfectly with great grammar.

782
00:46:48.960 --> 00:46:51.130
You never asked "why",
you never studied "why".

783
00:46:51.200 --> 00:46:52.650
Very important.

784
00:46:52.720 --> 00:46:55.170
Rule number five, input creates output.

785
00:46:55.240 --> 00:46:59.610
If you want to improve
your speaking, you need to listen more.

786
00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:02.250
If you to improve your writing,
you need to read more.

787
00:47:02.320 --> 00:47:07.210
So that's why we want to spend 99% of
your time on just listening and reading,

788
00:47:07.280 --> 00:47:09.650
listening and reading over
and over and over again.

789
00:47:09.720 --> 00:47:11.690
And your speaking ability will come.

790
00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:16.010
Your writing ability will come over time,
but it takes time.

791
00:47:16.080 --> 00:47:22.360
The input, what enters, is what creates
output, what goes out of your mouth

792
00:47:22.360 --> 00:47:23.810
and your finger when you write.

793
00:47:23.880 --> 00:47:28.600
So be patient and realize it
takes time to memorize language

794
00:47:28.670 --> 00:47:31.930
in your long-term memory,
but we need to give it more input.

795
00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:37.960
Think about your brain as a computer,
and you want to give your computer

796
00:47:38.030 --> 00:47:41.210
as much data, as much information
as possible to process.

797
00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:44.680
So input, input, input, listening,
listening, listening, reading,

798
00:47:44.680 --> 00:47:46.050
reading, listening, listening.

799
00:47:46.120 --> 00:47:48.160
That's the key!

800
00:47:48.230 --> 00:47:51.400
Rule number six,
comprehension over correctness.

801
00:47:52.280 --> 00:47:54.930
Don't worry about being correct.

802
00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:59.920
If you make a few mistakes when speaking,
if you have a few errors in your

803
00:47:59.990 --> 00:48:02.010
pronunciation, don't worry about that.

804
00:48:02.080 --> 00:48:06.280
You will correct all of those mistakes
through input, through consuming more,

805
00:48:06.280 --> 00:48:08.010
through advancing through the course.

806
00:48:08.080 --> 00:48:11.050
The most important thing is comprehension
that you actually understand.

807
00:48:11.120 --> 00:48:14.810
If you understand when people
speak to you, then you have fluency.

808
00:48:14.880 --> 00:48:18.850
If you're too worried about being correct,
you're going to get stuck,

809
00:48:18.920 --> 00:48:21.720
and you're going to become robotic,
and we don't want that.

810
00:48:21.750 --> 00:48:24.600
That's going to decrease fluency,
and that's going to take

811
00:48:24.670 --> 00:48:26.570
a toll on your confidence.

812
00:48:26.640 --> 00:48:30.370
We want to increase the fluency,
so focus on comprehension

813
00:48:30.440 --> 00:48:31.689
over correctness.

814
00:48:31.889 --> 00:48:35.730
Comprehension of complete messages,
complete sentences,

815
00:48:35.800 --> 00:48:40.320
not every single detail of the language.

816
00:48:40.400 --> 00:48:44.450
Number seven, just because you understand
everything doesn't mean it's too easy.

817
00:48:44.520 --> 00:48:48.280
This is very important if
you speak a little bit of English now

818
00:48:48.350 --> 00:48:52.320
and you start with
the first class here and you think,

819
00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:53.560
"Hmm, this is very easy for me."

820
00:48:53.560 --> 00:48:54.690
"I already speak English."

821
00:48:54.760 --> 00:48:58.200
Now, just because you understand
everything doesn't mean it's too easy.

822
00:48:58.260 --> 00:48:59.810
Repetition is your best friend.

823
00:48:59.880 --> 00:49:04.450
We need to repeat what we already
understand to memorize it deeper

824
00:49:04.520 --> 00:49:08.416
so that it can come out of your mouth
without translating in your head,

825
00:49:08.616 --> 00:49:11.290
without thinking,
automatically, intuitively.

826
00:49:11.360 --> 00:49:14.770
So repeating when you understand
is just good for you.

827
00:49:14.840 --> 00:49:17.080
If you already speak a little bit
of English when you get started,

828
00:49:17.150 --> 00:49:18.410
just be patient.

829
00:49:18.480 --> 00:49:20.850
You're going to advance faster
through the first sections,

830
00:49:20.920 --> 00:49:24.400
and that's fine, but then it's going
to catch up quickly, and you're going

831
